					<description><![CDATA[<p>Technology is changing how doctors detect colon cancer. New AI-enhanced imaging tools&nbsp;help&nbsp;physicians find subtle polyps that might otherwise be missed.&nbsp;Learn more from Dr. Michael Wallace, a Mayo Clinic gastroenterologist. Watch: The Mayo Clinic Minute Journalists: Broadcast-quality video (1:09) is in the downloads at the end of this post.&amp;#160;Please courtesy: "Mayo Clinic News Network." Read the&amp;#160;script. [&amp;#8230;]</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/discussion/mayo-clinic-minute-ai-advances-help-care-teams-find-hard-to-see-colon-polyps/">Mayo Clinic Minute: AI advances help care teams find hard-to-see colon polyps</a> appeared first on <a href="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org">Mayo Clinic News Network</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>Technology is changing how doctors detect <a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/colon-cancer/symptoms-causes/syc-20353669" id="https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/colon-cancer/symptoms-causes/syc-20353669" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">colon cancer</a>. New AI-enhanced imaging tools&nbsp;help&nbsp;physicians find subtle polyps that might otherwise be missed.&nbsp;Learn more from <a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/biographies/wallace-michael-b-m-d/bio-20569473" id="https://www.mayoclinic.org/biographies/wallace-michael-b-m-d/bio-20569473" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Dr. Michael Wallace</a>, a Mayo Clinic gastroenterologist.</p>



<p><strong><a href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=BYxcD2rfBPo&amp;amp;feature=youtu.be" id="youtube.com/watch?v=BYxcD2rfBPo&amp;amp;feature=youtu.be" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Watch: The Mayo Clinic Minute</a></strong></p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<div class="fluidEmbed"><iframe id="videoidhttpsyoutubeBYxcD2rfBPo"  title="Mayo Clinic Minute: AI advances help care teams find hard-to-see colon polyps" width="500" height="281" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/BYxcD2rfBPo?feature=oembed&amp;enablejsapi=1" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>
</div></figure>



<p><strong>Journalists: Broadcast-quality video (1:09) is in the downloads at the end of this post.&amp;nbsp;Please courtesy: "Mayo Clinic News Network." Read the&amp;nbsp;<a href="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2026/03/Mayo-Clinic-Minute-AI-advances-help-care-teams-find-hard-to-see-colon-polyps_Script.pdf" id="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2026/03/Mayo-Clinic-Minute-AI-advances-help-care-teams-find-hard-to-see-colon-polyps_Script.pdf">script</a>.</strong></p>



<p><a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/colon-polyps/symptoms-causes/syc-20352875" id="https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/colon-polyps/symptoms-causes/syc-20352875">Polyps</a> in the colon can vary in size and shape. Some are more&nbsp;mushroom-shaped, but that's not always the case.&nbsp;</p>



<p>"Some polyps spread out more like a bed of moss; they're flat," says Dr. Wallace.</p>



<p>Advances in imaging and tools help care teams detect and treat difficult polyps.&amp;nbsp;</p>



<p>"Technology has been clearly shown to improve our ability to find more polyps and reduce the miss rate for some of these flat, subtle polyps," says Dr. Wallace.&amp;nbsp;</p>



<p>Early detection leads to better outcomes.&amp;nbsp;</p>



<p>"Stage 1 cancer, so-called T1 cancer, we can actually remove that through an endoscope or through a colonoscope, specifically, in a curative way," says Dr. Wallace. "This is something that has had profound implications for patient care."&amp;nbsp;</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter size-large is-resized"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2026/03/Colon-polyps-illustration-Mayo-16x9-1-1024x576.jpg" alt="Medical illustration of colon polyps, colorectal cancer stages" class="wp-image-411943" style="width:596px;height:auto" srcset="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2026/03/Colon-polyps-illustration-Mayo-16x9-1-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2026/03/Colon-polyps-illustration-Mayo-16x9-1-300x169.jpg 300w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2026/03/Colon-polyps-illustration-Mayo-16x9-1-768x432.jpg 768w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2026/03/Colon-polyps-illustration-Mayo-16x9-1-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2026/03/Colon-polyps-illustration-Mayo-16x9-1.jpg 1753w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>
</div>


<p>Dr. Wallace adds that the most important step is to get screened.&amp;nbsp;</p>



<p>"Whatever test you choose, get screened," Dr. Wallace says. "This is&amp;nbsp;a preventable cancer. It's one of the very few cancers that we can almost completely prevent. So getting screened starting at the age of 45 — one caveat is — if you have a family history of colon cancer, you need to start even earlier."</p>



